00:00:26.010 --> 00:00:31.750
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Now, this
is how we left on Tuesday.

00:00:31.750 --> 00:00:36.820
We got to this point where we
had put a particle in a box.

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:39.860
We put a quantum mechanical
particle in a box.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:42.400
And it was an
infinite square well.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:44.404
And what's this called?

00:00:44.404 --> 00:00:45.568
AUDIENCE: Energy levels.

00:00:45.568 --> 00:00:47.360
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Energy
levels, and what's

00:00:47.360 --> 00:00:49.262
really weird about them?

00:00:49.262 --> 00:00:50.720
AUDIENCE: They're discrete.

00:00:50.720 --> 00:00:54.680
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah, meaning
if you have this one here

00:00:54.680 --> 00:00:56.540
and then you have
another energy here,

00:00:56.540 --> 00:00:58.670
can it have energy in between?

00:00:58.670 --> 00:00:59.493
No.

00:00:59.493 --> 00:01:01.160
Can that quantum
particle be in between?

00:01:01.160 --> 00:01:02.880
No, in energy.

00:01:02.880 --> 00:01:04.970
And so the question
was, can we connect that

00:01:04.970 --> 00:01:07.550
to things like what we
see in the universe,

00:01:07.550 --> 00:01:09.140
like the spectral lines?

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:10.795
So what I want to do--

00:01:10.795 --> 00:01:12.170
there's a little
bit more we need

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:15.240
to do to do that connection.

00:01:15.240 --> 00:01:18.440
And so I want to spend some time
today just going through that

00:01:18.440 --> 00:01:21.650
and going to the hydrogen
atom, because this is not

00:01:21.650 --> 00:01:22.400
the hydrogen atom.

00:01:22.400 --> 00:01:23.990
It's not an infinite well.

00:01:23.990 --> 00:01:28.160
And then from the
hydrogen atom, we'll

00:01:28.160 --> 00:01:31.820
talk about how just
from that, just

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:33.800
by solving for
the hydrogen atom,

00:01:33.800 --> 00:01:37.430
we literally have this
incredibly deep understanding

00:01:37.430 --> 00:01:40.870
of the entire periodic
table and all of chemistry.

00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:42.930
So it's a pretty
powerful thing to do.

00:01:42.930 --> 00:01:45.530
So we're going to start
with a little bit of review,

00:01:45.530 --> 00:01:49.032
and then this
real-world example.

00:01:49.032 --> 00:01:50.990
And then I've got to tell
you a few things that

00:01:50.990 --> 00:01:54.230
are really important, like you
have this thing called "spin."

00:01:54.230 --> 00:01:55.520
So we'll talk about that.

00:01:55.520 --> 00:02:00.290
We'll end with that, and talk
about how from this solution,

00:02:00.290 --> 00:02:01.490
you get this--

00:02:01.490 --> 00:02:04.870
pretty awesome, pretty amazing.

00:02:04.870 --> 00:02:09.340
So some review-- so we went
through this on Tuesday.

00:02:09.340 --> 00:02:14.320
So why did people even
need quantum mechanics?

00:02:14.320 --> 00:02:16.530
Well, because things were
failing, and crumbling,

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:20.070
and catastrophing
all around them.

00:02:22.640 --> 00:02:24.110
And so how long--

00:02:24.110 --> 00:02:28.850
so classical atom, oh, no,
there's a classical atom.

00:02:28.850 --> 00:02:30.620
Photoelectric effect
was one of them.

00:02:30.620 --> 00:02:35.050
Who can explain
what happened here?

00:02:35.050 --> 00:02:37.450
These are some of the
reasons why we needed

00:02:37.450 --> 00:02:41.913
a new theory after 400 years.

00:02:41.913 --> 00:02:43.830
What's going on with the
photoelectric effect?

00:02:51.610 --> 00:02:52.780
Anyone remember?

00:02:52.780 --> 00:02:54.490
Yeah.

00:02:54.490 --> 00:02:59.013
AUDIENCE: A description of the
phenomenon or why it happened?

00:02:59.013 --> 00:02:59.930
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yes.

00:02:59.930 --> 00:03:02.680
AUDIENCE: OK, so basically,
you take some light.

00:03:02.680 --> 00:03:06.320
You shine it at a metal, and
a bunch of electrons come off.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:08.560
And if you increase the
intensity of the light,

00:03:08.560 --> 00:03:10.090
the number of
electrons coming off

00:03:10.090 --> 00:03:11.710
increases, but not
the energy, which

00:03:11.710 --> 00:03:13.490
was sort of counterintuitive.

00:03:13.490 --> 00:03:15.490
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Why was
that counterintuitive?

00:03:15.490 --> 00:03:18.670
AUDIENCE: Because if
light's not a particle,

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:21.670
it's just like a
wave, then you expect

00:03:21.670 --> 00:03:24.260
if you're shooting more light
at it, that's more energy.

00:03:24.260 --> 00:03:26.920
So if an electron gets
hit by a bunch of light,

00:03:26.920 --> 00:03:29.230
you'd think it would
get a bunch of energy,

00:03:29.230 --> 00:03:31.750
and you'd also get a higher
energy, but it doesn't.

00:03:31.750 --> 00:03:34.840
And the solution
was that the photons

00:03:34.840 --> 00:03:36.970
are produced by electrons
changing energy levels

00:03:36.970 --> 00:03:38.330
or something like that.

00:03:38.330 --> 00:03:41.445
And so they come in
discrete packets of energy.

00:03:41.445 --> 00:03:42.820
And so when they
hit an electron,

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:44.800
they shoot it off at
some particular energy.

00:03:44.800 --> 00:03:45.470
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
And what's that?

00:03:45.470 --> 00:03:46.210
AUDIENCE: It's
frequency dependent.

00:03:46.210 --> 00:03:47.950
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: It's just
dependent on the frequency,

00:03:47.950 --> 00:03:48.545
exactly.

00:03:48.545 --> 00:03:49.420
That's exactly right.

00:03:49.420 --> 00:03:50.920
So does everybody see that?

00:03:50.920 --> 00:03:53.440
So this was called the
"photoelectric effect."

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:58.750
And it was the reason Einstein
was given the Nobel Prize.

00:03:58.750 --> 00:04:01.840
It's a very
important explanation

00:04:01.840 --> 00:04:03.832
of this very confusing
effect, which

00:04:03.832 --> 00:04:05.290
is that you increase
the intensity,

00:04:05.290 --> 00:04:07.075
but the energy of
those electrons--

00:04:07.075 --> 00:04:07.950
see what's happening?

00:04:07.950 --> 00:04:10.575
You're shining light on a piece
of metal and electrons fly off.

00:04:10.575 --> 00:04:13.840
And you can measure how much
energy those electrons have.

00:04:13.840 --> 00:04:15.520
And you increase the
intensity of light,

00:04:15.520 --> 00:04:18.130
and they don't have any more
energy, which was really

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:20.410
bizarre if light is a wave.

00:04:20.410 --> 00:04:24.130
What Einstein said
is, no, actually, oh,

00:04:24.130 --> 00:04:27.990
but it does depend on the
frequency of the light.

00:04:27.990 --> 00:04:30.590
So that makes sense if
light can be considered

00:04:30.590 --> 00:04:34.500
as particles of zero mass--

00:04:34.500 --> 00:04:38.490
that's weird-- that have
an energy associated

00:04:38.490 --> 00:04:39.960
with their frequency.

00:04:39.960 --> 00:04:41.240
So that was really important.

00:04:41.240 --> 00:04:44.160
The energy of
something you thought

00:04:44.160 --> 00:04:47.850
was a wave, light,
actually can be considered

00:04:47.850 --> 00:04:50.220
as a particle associated
with the frequency,

00:04:50.220 --> 00:04:53.310
have the energy of a particle
associated with that frequency.

00:04:53.310 --> 00:04:55.320
And then what was
the classical atom?

00:04:55.320 --> 00:04:58.010
What's wrong with this one?

00:04:58.010 --> 00:05:02.800
How long do we live
in a classical world?

00:05:02.800 --> 00:05:05.086
What's the most we could
live in a classical world?

00:05:05.086 --> 00:05:06.790
AUDIENCE: 10 to the
minus 12 seconds.

00:05:06.790 --> 00:05:09.460
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: 10 to the
minus 12 seconds, it's game

00:05:09.460 --> 00:05:10.000
over.

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:10.750
Why?

00:05:10.750 --> 00:05:13.735
What's happening?

00:05:13.735 --> 00:05:16.433
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:05:16.433 --> 00:05:17.350
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Why?

00:05:17.350 --> 00:05:18.058
What's happening?

00:05:18.058 --> 00:05:19.940
So it's accelerating,
and we know

00:05:19.940 --> 00:05:22.250
that an accelerating charge--

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:25.248
radiation, and it loses energy.

00:05:25.248 --> 00:05:27.290
And if it loses energy,
it should just spiral in,

00:05:27.290 --> 00:05:30.570
and that takes about 10
to the minus 12 seconds.

00:05:30.570 --> 00:05:32.720
So we know that's
not true, either.

00:05:32.720 --> 00:05:34.910
Actually, I wanted to
put this out there.

00:05:34.910 --> 00:05:40.590
This is from Wikipedia, and it's
a sort of explanation of that.

00:05:40.590 --> 00:05:42.770
And so if you want to
understand more and read more

00:05:42.770 --> 00:05:45.380
about the classical
atom, get a book

00:05:45.380 --> 00:05:48.245
on Lienard-Wiechert potentials.

00:05:48.245 --> 00:05:50.120
I'm sure just the name
alone is inspiring you

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:53.870
guys to want to dig deep.

00:05:53.870 --> 00:05:55.160
And those are the ones.

00:05:55.160 --> 00:05:58.310
That's what you can do to
get the time-varying EM

00:05:58.310 --> 00:06:01.100
field for a point charge
in arbitrary motion.

00:06:01.100 --> 00:06:02.840
But look at that--
they're not corrected

00:06:02.840 --> 00:06:04.132
for quantum mechanical effects.

00:06:06.550 --> 00:06:08.710
So that's what was
such a problem.

00:06:08.710 --> 00:06:12.310
This was right around 1900.

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:15.670
So they had it, but then they
tried to apply it to an atom,

00:06:15.670 --> 00:06:17.300
and here's what happens.

00:06:17.300 --> 00:06:21.457
It's accurate, but breaks
down at the quantum level.

00:06:21.457 --> 00:06:23.290
Quantum mechanics sets
important constraints

00:06:23.290 --> 00:06:26.800
on the ability of a particle
to emit radiation, i.e.,

00:06:26.800 --> 00:06:29.040
it doesn't in an atom.

00:06:31.433 --> 00:06:33.850
Sometimes, I think this is
kind of interesting to look at.

00:06:33.850 --> 00:06:37.060
Basically, we have this
problem that an atom will

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:39.888
sort of self-destruct, and the
electrons just spiral down.

00:06:39.888 --> 00:06:41.680
The solution really,
if you think about it,

00:06:41.680 --> 00:06:44.920
is it doesn't do that anymore.

00:06:44.920 --> 00:06:46.030
But now why?

00:06:46.030 --> 00:06:51.320
Well, because of the fact that
particles are waves and waves

00:06:51.320 --> 00:06:52.070
are particles.

00:06:52.070 --> 00:06:54.900
And it comes from
the quantization.

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:59.930
So I want to make sure
that we're all on that page

00:06:59.930 --> 00:07:02.120
by the end of today, that
we all kind of see that.

00:07:02.120 --> 00:07:05.900
So that's the reason,
is because particles can

00:07:05.900 --> 00:07:10.130
be both waves and particles.

00:07:10.130 --> 00:07:12.440
Waves can be waves
and particles.

00:07:12.440 --> 00:07:16.610
Everything is one happy family.

00:07:16.610 --> 00:07:18.350
Can't we all just get along?

00:07:18.350 --> 00:07:20.750
Here are some particles
going through slits.

00:07:20.750 --> 00:07:21.860
Now what's happening here?

00:07:25.700 --> 00:07:27.590
Actually, you can think
of this as a particle

00:07:27.590 --> 00:07:31.540
or it kind of looks like
a water wave, doesn't it?

00:07:31.540 --> 00:07:33.160
But see, that's the whole point.

00:07:33.160 --> 00:07:34.630
That's what particles are.

00:07:37.590 --> 00:07:39.360
So what's happening here?

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:44.090
Can somebody explain
why it's showing this?

00:07:44.090 --> 00:07:44.810
What's going on?

00:07:47.612 --> 00:07:51.876
We've got on the
left, how many slits?

00:07:51.876 --> 00:07:52.630
AUDIENCE: One.

00:07:52.630 --> 00:07:52.990
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
And on the right?

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:53.770
AUDIENCE: Two.

00:07:53.770 --> 00:07:56.170
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
What's the difference?

00:07:56.170 --> 00:07:57.280
AUDIENCE: Interference.

00:07:57.280 --> 00:07:58.480
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yes.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:01.300
What's interference?

00:08:01.300 --> 00:08:03.008
AUDIENCE: Two different
waves, and you've

00:08:03.008 --> 00:08:03.925
got peaks and troughs.

00:08:03.925 --> 00:08:06.730
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah, so that
you get two waves coming out

00:08:06.730 --> 00:08:12.190
of-- but look, the same particle
creates no interference here

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:14.030
because it just bubbles through.

00:08:14.030 --> 00:08:19.210
But if you have two slits, it
can create two little waves.

00:08:19.210 --> 00:08:22.430
And those interfere and
they cause complex behavior.

00:08:22.430 --> 00:08:25.658
And that is what
blew people away.

00:08:25.658 --> 00:08:27.700
And oh, by the way, you
can see that there's also

00:08:27.700 --> 00:08:29.283
some really cool
interference going on

00:08:29.283 --> 00:08:31.282
in the backscattering
from the edges,

00:08:31.282 --> 00:08:32.740
because you get a
little scattering

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:34.880
off the edges on both cases.

00:08:34.880 --> 00:08:37.669
But what we're looking at is
what's happening over here.

00:08:37.669 --> 00:08:40.169
And so it's just really weird
that you could throw particles

00:08:40.169 --> 00:08:42.600
through slits, and they
were like water waves,

00:08:42.600 --> 00:08:43.890
not like particles.

00:08:43.890 --> 00:08:49.680
That was another really
bizarre experiment.

00:08:49.680 --> 00:08:55.660
And again, one of the big,
important stepping stones

00:08:55.660 --> 00:08:59.290
was the fact that you
could describe the energy

00:08:59.290 --> 00:09:00.940
of a particle by its frequency.

00:09:00.940 --> 00:09:06.180
And then de Broglie came and
said, actually, not just light.

00:09:06.180 --> 00:09:09.300
No, everything-- all matter--

00:09:09.300 --> 00:09:12.550
can be considered as both
a particle and a wave.

00:09:12.550 --> 00:09:14.760
This is stuff we
talked about Tuesday.

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:18.330
And so what that means is
that I have a wavelength.

00:09:18.330 --> 00:09:21.560
What's my wavelength?

00:09:21.560 --> 00:09:24.290
35, 10 to the minus 35.

00:09:24.290 --> 00:09:25.940
But I'm OK with that.

00:09:25.940 --> 00:09:30.560
I feel that quantum
is right here.

00:09:30.560 --> 00:09:35.030
I feel it somewhere within.

00:09:35.030 --> 00:09:39.710
But see, when things are really
small like an electron, which

00:09:39.710 --> 00:09:42.320
is this part of the class--
we care about those electrons.

00:09:42.320 --> 00:09:46.040
And I motivated that on Tuesday,
and we'll come back to that

00:09:46.040 --> 00:09:48.120
as we go through examples.

00:09:48.120 --> 00:09:50.570
So if I want to know
about an electron,

00:09:50.570 --> 00:09:52.190
that's a really small thing.

00:09:52.190 --> 00:09:56.450
And so its wavelength-- and
we talked about this Tuesday--

00:09:56.450 --> 00:09:59.570
the wavelength associated
with the particle

00:09:59.570 --> 00:10:03.500
is about the same
size as the distances

00:10:03.500 --> 00:10:05.480
the particle sort of
goes out for a walk

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:10.010
on, on a daily basis, otherwise
known as its "chemical bond."

00:10:10.010 --> 00:10:11.960
If you're an electron,
you kind of walk

00:10:11.960 --> 00:10:14.090
along this chemical bond.

00:10:14.090 --> 00:10:20.390
That's sort of what you do, if
you're in a bonding situation.

00:10:20.390 --> 00:10:24.170
And that distance of that
walk is roughly the same

00:10:24.170 --> 00:10:27.800
as your wavelength,
as your wave nature.

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:33.370
Your wave nature-ness
is important then.

00:10:33.370 --> 00:10:35.770
And so because of that,
we can't describe it

00:10:35.770 --> 00:10:37.060
without quantum mechanics.

00:10:37.060 --> 00:10:40.590
You have to have a
way of describing it.

00:10:40.590 --> 00:10:44.060
And it has to be something
that is based on a wave.

00:10:44.060 --> 00:10:45.980
So that's the breakthrough.

00:10:45.980 --> 00:10:48.620
And I'll go through
that again just quickly.

00:10:51.290 --> 00:10:58.550
But what we came out with is the
fact that particles are waves.

00:10:58.550 --> 00:11:00.800
So they have wave functions.

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:03.740
And this wave function is
what we'll be solving for.

00:11:03.740 --> 00:11:06.050
This is what we want in
this part of the class.

00:11:06.050 --> 00:11:06.920
We want that.

00:11:10.550 --> 00:11:12.560
And so it'll have some form.

00:11:12.560 --> 00:11:15.170
And we showed a few forms,
and I'll show you more today.

00:11:15.170 --> 00:11:17.480
But we showed a few for
a particle in a box.

00:11:17.480 --> 00:11:24.350
That had a cosine, and then
it had one node in the middle.

00:11:24.350 --> 00:11:28.730
But what's amazing about this
is that this has no meaning

00:11:28.730 --> 00:11:30.060
we know of.

00:11:30.060 --> 00:11:32.340
We do not understand
what this means.

00:11:32.340 --> 00:11:38.000
So you have this
intimate function

00:11:38.000 --> 00:11:40.800
that describes the
particle, and we

00:11:40.800 --> 00:11:43.940
don't know how to interpret it.

00:11:43.940 --> 00:11:48.710
The big breakthrough came
in making the connection

00:11:48.710 --> 00:11:54.080
that the square of that
function is meaningful.

00:11:54.080 --> 00:11:55.310
But that's pretty cool.

00:11:55.310 --> 00:11:58.100
So think about if
I had a position.

00:11:58.100 --> 00:11:59.430
Wait, you had this--

00:11:59.430 --> 00:12:02.000
you did classical
molecular dynamics,

00:12:02.000 --> 00:12:04.100
so you have the position
of the particle.

00:12:04.100 --> 00:12:06.740
That's a function of time.

00:12:06.740 --> 00:12:08.560
Imagine saying that
that has no meaning,

00:12:08.560 --> 00:12:12.100
or you don't know what it
means, only the square of it.

00:12:12.100 --> 00:12:14.110
So something as
fundamental as the wave

00:12:14.110 --> 00:12:18.810
itself that is the solution
to the equation to our f

00:12:18.810 --> 00:12:22.290
equals ma, which is Schrodinger,
something as fundamental

00:12:22.290 --> 00:12:24.720
as that, we don't
know what it means.

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:27.400
But we do know what
its square means.

00:12:27.400 --> 00:12:28.760
And what does the square mean?

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:29.960
AUDIENCE: Probability.

00:12:29.960 --> 00:12:31.210
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Probability.

00:12:31.210 --> 00:12:34.416
So tell me a little
more about that.

00:12:34.416 --> 00:12:36.840
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:12:36.840 --> 00:12:39.870
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah, so tell
me-- this is a particle right

00:12:39.870 --> 00:12:40.370
here.

00:12:40.370 --> 00:12:42.920
You're starting to
see it, I can tell.

00:12:42.920 --> 00:12:45.540
I can see that you're
starting to see it.

00:12:45.540 --> 00:12:49.220
I can feel the excitement
about this, too, in the room.

00:12:49.220 --> 00:12:50.570
It's tangible.

