00:32:01.520 --> 00:32:06.890
So that's a little motivation
for hydrogen. Now here it is.

00:32:06.890 --> 00:32:10.270
Hydrogen has a
proton, an electron,

00:32:10.270 --> 00:32:14.830
and it's got some distance
that that electron sits away

00:32:14.830 --> 00:32:17.070
from the proton.

00:32:17.070 --> 00:32:18.690
What do I need to know?

00:32:18.690 --> 00:32:25.300
Well, I need to
know the potential.

00:32:25.300 --> 00:32:28.420
So what's the potential here
between these two charges?

00:32:28.420 --> 00:32:29.920
One's negative, one's positive.

00:32:29.920 --> 00:32:32.880
They feel an attraction.

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:36.600
How does it go with r?

00:32:36.600 --> 00:32:37.770
Yeah.

00:32:37.770 --> 00:32:39.960
It goes as 1 over r.

00:32:39.960 --> 00:32:46.140
So now that-- I got my
V. It's the potential

00:32:46.140 --> 00:32:47.550
that charges feel.

00:32:47.550 --> 00:32:50.940
And that's got to go now into
the Schrodinger equation, which

00:32:50.940 --> 00:32:51.990
I then need to solve.

00:32:51.990 --> 00:32:57.870
And that'll tell me what the
possible wave functions are.

00:32:57.870 --> 00:32:59.550
And so here's what
it looks like, see?

00:32:59.550 --> 00:33:01.410
We had H psi equals E psi.

00:33:01.410 --> 00:33:03.570
That's our master equation.

00:33:03.570 --> 00:33:06.690
Then we said, that's the
kinetic plus potential.

00:33:06.690 --> 00:33:09.900
And then we said, that's
the momentum term, remember,

00:33:09.900 --> 00:33:13.630
we talked about Tuesday, which
is just a second derivative.

00:33:13.630 --> 00:33:15.100
It's a second
partial derivative.

00:33:15.100 --> 00:33:18.390
It's a del squared, and plus
this potential term, which

00:33:18.390 --> 00:33:23.970
I now put in here explicitly
for the hydrogen atom, E

00:33:23.970 --> 00:33:26.780
squared over 4 pi epsilon 0 r.

00:33:26.780 --> 00:33:30.090
And that's the question
I need to solve.

00:33:30.090 --> 00:33:35.260
And it turns out that you
can solve this exactly.

00:33:35.260 --> 00:33:37.170
You can solve this
exactly, just like you

00:33:37.170 --> 00:33:41.170
could the particle in the box
with the infinite boundaries.

00:33:41.170 --> 00:33:43.620
And that's really cool.

00:33:43.620 --> 00:33:45.520
So you've got an electron.

00:33:45.520 --> 00:33:49.370
You've got one particle,
just one electron.

00:33:49.370 --> 00:33:51.410
These are its
spatial coordinates.

00:33:51.410 --> 00:33:53.510
And you can solve for
it in this potential,

00:33:53.510 --> 00:33:56.810
in this 1 over r
potential exactly.

00:33:56.810 --> 00:33:59.690
And the easy way to do that
is to switch it to spherical

00:33:59.690 --> 00:34:00.700
coordinates.

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:03.620
So I won't go through
the math in detail.

00:34:03.620 --> 00:34:07.790
There's literally like 100
sites and 50 Wolfram Alpha apps

00:34:07.790 --> 00:34:11.090
you can look at that
go through this,

00:34:11.090 --> 00:34:14.960
and really, really
wonderful material on this.

00:34:14.960 --> 00:34:18.800
But basically, the key point
is that when you write it

00:34:18.800 --> 00:34:23.239
in spherical coordinates,
you switch from XYZ Cartesian

00:34:23.239 --> 00:34:27.080
to spherical coordinates, you
can actually separate this

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:35.929
into essentially three quantized
problems-- theta, r, and phi.

00:34:35.929 --> 00:34:40.130
And so you can write psi
now as a function of the r

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:42.830
and a function of the theta
and a function of the phi.

00:34:42.830 --> 00:34:46.175
And what ends up happening--
and then so you put that in.

00:34:46.175 --> 00:34:47.550
And there's a
little bit of math.

00:34:47.550 --> 00:34:48.949
It's actually not that much.

00:34:48.949 --> 00:34:51.031
I'm not going to go through it.

00:34:51.031 --> 00:34:52.489
But you put that
in, and basically,

00:34:52.489 --> 00:34:55.850
just like that
particle in the box,

00:34:55.850 --> 00:35:01.420
just like that, each one of
these variables gets quantized.

00:35:01.420 --> 00:35:05.620
It gets its own
sort of E-type term,

00:35:05.620 --> 00:35:09.160
and it gets a quantization.

00:35:09.160 --> 00:35:12.190
So these are the
equations that it

00:35:12.190 --> 00:35:15.350
leads to when you do the
separation of variables.

00:35:15.350 --> 00:35:20.740
And I think I have-- yes,
and the quantization is--

00:35:20.740 --> 00:35:23.590
I think maybe on the next page
I have the actual energies.

00:35:23.590 --> 00:35:26.140
But the solution--
remember, just

00:35:26.140 --> 00:35:28.720
like the quantization of a
particle in a box, the same

00:35:28.720 --> 00:35:29.410
here.

00:35:29.410 --> 00:35:32.710
It only can happen, you
can only have a solution,

00:35:32.710 --> 00:35:34.420
if in this case,
we're going to have

00:35:34.420 --> 00:35:39.070
a quantum number called n is 1,
2, 3, or something else going

00:35:39.070 --> 00:35:39.670
up.

00:35:39.670 --> 00:35:42.370
Or in this case, we'll have
a quantum number called l.

