That means the energy of an
electron in this first orbital,

00:40:38.960 --> 00:40:42.590
that one up there, if I put
an electron in that orbital,

00:40:42.590 --> 00:40:50.342
its energy is bound to
the atom by 13.6 eV.

00:40:50.342 --> 00:40:51.300
So what does that mean?

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:54.640
Yeah.

00:40:54.640 --> 00:40:59.112
AUDIENCE: If you give it 13.6 eV
or greater, it'll become free.

00:40:59.112 --> 00:41:00.070
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah.

00:41:00.070 --> 00:41:03.850
That's the ionization
energy of that electron.

00:41:03.850 --> 00:41:07.630
But hydrogen has all
of these other orbitals

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:08.830
accessible to it.

00:41:08.830 --> 00:41:13.000
Maybe I could put an
electron up to another level,

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:16.060
like the 2s level.

00:41:16.060 --> 00:41:20.560
And if I do that, it's
all the way up to 3.4.

00:41:20.560 --> 00:41:24.260
So now it's only bound
by 3.4 eV in the atom.

00:41:24.260 --> 00:41:25.960
And what does that make it?

00:41:31.650 --> 00:41:35.410
Is it sort of less
stable, more stable?

00:41:35.410 --> 00:41:36.327
AUDIENCE: Less stable.

00:41:36.327 --> 00:41:37.577
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Less stable.

00:41:37.577 --> 00:41:39.408
So it'd be much more
easy to pull it off.

00:41:39.408 --> 00:41:41.950
Now, do you think that that has
something to do with bonding?

00:41:45.430 --> 00:41:47.950
You better believe it.

00:41:47.950 --> 00:41:55.060
Where electrons sit in energy
relative to other electrons

00:41:55.060 --> 00:41:57.760
in other atoms, or
in their own atom,

00:41:57.760 --> 00:42:02.850
has everything to do with
how things bond together.

00:42:02.850 --> 00:42:04.800
And that bonding is
the one that you've

00:42:04.800 --> 00:42:09.140
been just fitting to like
a Lennard-Jones potential.

00:42:09.140 --> 00:42:10.400
You've just been fitting it.

00:42:10.400 --> 00:42:13.400
All that bonding is what you
just-- in classical physics,

00:42:13.400 --> 00:42:18.650
in classical modeling, you have
to have some potential form.

00:42:18.650 --> 00:42:20.930
And all of the
intricacies of the bonding

00:42:20.930 --> 00:42:22.370
get swept up into that.

00:42:22.370 --> 00:42:24.410
But you can see why
that's so much more

00:42:24.410 --> 00:42:29.090
complicated than that,
just by looking at these.

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:32.840
OK, but now, that
series that we just

00:42:32.840 --> 00:42:37.340
got from a simple particle
in 1 over r potential

00:42:37.340 --> 00:42:43.550
explains all of these
levels that are observed.

00:42:43.550 --> 00:42:45.950
So does everybody remember this?

00:42:45.950 --> 00:42:50.570
And poor number six
who didn't get named?

00:42:50.570 --> 00:42:51.540
What are these?

00:42:54.730 --> 00:42:58.630
When you see these, what
does it make you think?

00:42:58.630 --> 00:43:06.110
Spectral-- now explain what's
happening in the Lymann series.

00:43:06.110 --> 00:43:07.140
What's happening?

00:43:07.140 --> 00:43:09.765
AUDIENCE: You're moving from one
orbital down to the ground one

00:43:09.765 --> 00:43:12.075
and it's emitting photons
at those wavelengths.

00:43:12.075 --> 00:43:13.950
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: And
why are they different?

00:43:13.950 --> 00:43:17.270
Why do I have all these
different ones in one series?

00:43:17.270 --> 00:43:19.974
AUDIENCE: The amount of energy
it gives off as it goes from n

00:43:19.974 --> 00:43:22.980
equals 7 to n equals 1 is
different from n equals 2 to n

00:43:22.980 --> 00:43:23.480
equals 1.

00:43:23.480 --> 00:43:25.020
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: Yeah, exactly.

00:43:25.020 --> 00:43:27.590
And if you go up to
2 and you stop at 2,

00:43:27.590 --> 00:43:29.720
then you have other energies.

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:33.620
Because it all comes down to,
then, what the differences are.

00:43:33.620 --> 00:43:36.680
To get an electron to
go from here to here,

00:43:36.680 --> 00:43:38.870
you need the difference
in these energies.

00:43:38.870 --> 00:43:41.270
And to go from here to here,
you need that difference.

00:43:41.270 --> 00:43:44.520
No more and no less will do.

00:43:44.520 --> 00:43:48.420
Now, when the electron comes
back down, what happens?

00:43:52.040 --> 00:43:55.438
Anybody know what happens?

00:43:55.438 --> 00:43:56.480
AUDIENCE: It emits light.

00:43:56.480 --> 00:43:57.855
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
It emits light.

00:43:57.855 --> 00:43:59.870
It gives that energy
back out as light.

00:43:59.870 --> 00:44:01.940
And that's what you
see when you look out

00:44:01.940 --> 00:44:03.500
at these spectral lines.

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:07.360
So it emits light at
exactly this energy.

00:44:07.360 --> 00:44:09.460
Can it emit light
at something else,

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:12.430
at a different amount of energy,
or a different frequency?

00:44:12.430 --> 00:44:15.640
Because we know for
light, the energy

00:44:15.640 --> 00:44:20.350
is equal to the frequency
times a constant.

00:44:20.350 --> 00:44:23.435
Can it emit light
at this frequency,

00:44:23.435 --> 00:44:24.310
something in between?

00:44:24.310 --> 00:44:24.810
Why not?

00:44:28.224 --> 00:44:29.210
AUDIENCE: Quantized.

00:44:29.210 --> 00:44:32.660
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
Yeah, it just can't

00:44:32.660 --> 00:44:38.600
because it's a wave
problem that has

00:44:38.600 --> 00:44:42.540
as its solution quantization.

00:44:42.540 --> 00:44:46.320
And now, I come to the question
of, well then how does--

00:44:46.320 --> 00:44:47.730
so that's what's happening.

00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:50.425
That's the picture of these
electrons coming back down,

00:44:50.425 --> 00:44:52.050
and emitting different
colors of light.

00:44:52.050 --> 00:44:55.620
It explains what
people saw and couldn't

00:44:55.620 --> 00:44:57.660
understand for so long.

00:44:57.660 --> 00:45:00.900
This simple solution,
mathematical solution,

00:45:00.900 --> 00:45:01.800
does it all.

00:45:01.800 --> 00:45:06.660
It really crystallized
what was going on,

00:45:06.660 --> 00:45:08.760
and it really confirmed
that this is the right way

00:45:08.760 --> 00:45:10.920
to picture things--

00:45:10.920 --> 00:45:14.790
the wave equation and
the Schrodinger equation.

00:45:14.790 --> 00:45:17.160
Now, what's happening when
an electron goes from here

00:45:17.160 --> 00:45:18.750
to here?

00:45:18.750 --> 00:45:21.980
How does it do that?

00:45:21.980 --> 00:45:28.400
It cannot go in between, but
we know it does do this all

00:45:28.400 --> 00:45:29.310
the time.

00:45:29.310 --> 00:45:31.935
We just look out in space and we
see it happening all the time,

00:45:31.935 --> 00:45:33.240
but we can do it here.

00:45:33.240 --> 00:45:37.910
We can build materials
that do this for a living.

00:45:37.910 --> 00:45:43.760
Where are those electrons
going when they go from the 2p

00:45:43.760 --> 00:45:46.690
to the 1s?

00:45:46.690 --> 00:45:47.940
Where are they going?

00:45:51.720 --> 00:45:54.640
Who can tell me?

00:45:54.640 --> 00:45:55.722
Yeah.

00:45:55.722 --> 00:45:58.180
AUDIENCE: They're all sort of
described by a wave function,

00:45:58.180 --> 00:45:58.680
right?

00:45:58.680 --> 00:46:00.700
So it has some
non-zero probability

00:46:00.700 --> 00:46:03.432
to be in one place and
a non-zero probability

00:46:03.432 --> 00:46:04.390
to be in another place.

00:46:04.390 --> 00:46:06.700
And if you hit it with
a photon or something,

00:46:06.700 --> 00:46:09.223
or have some perturbation
to your hydrogen atom,

00:46:09.223 --> 00:46:11.140
then it's going to have
a non-zero probability

00:46:11.140 --> 00:46:13.700
to be in one electron
energy level than another.

00:46:13.700 --> 00:46:17.087
And so it just sort of ends
up falling into one of them.

00:46:17.087 --> 00:46:18.670
JEFFREY GROSSMAN:
That actually works.

00:46:18.670 --> 00:46:23.142
That is a great interpretation
of what's happening.

00:46:23.142 --> 00:46:25.600
And that actually works, and
it even works all the way down

00:46:25.600 --> 00:46:26.260
to the nucleus.

00:46:26.260 --> 00:46:30.250
By the way, decay to
the nucleus is possible

00:46:30.250 --> 00:46:33.400
because those s orbitals--

00:46:33.400 --> 00:46:36.670
I was just showing you a
slice of them, an isosurface.

00:46:36.670 --> 00:46:40.420
But they have a non-zero
magnitude all the way down

00:46:40.420 --> 00:46:41.290
to the nucleus.

00:46:41.290 --> 00:46:46.450
It just won't happen very often,
because the probability is

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:52.840
so low that it's why
we have a universe.

00:46:52.840 --> 00:46:57.190
If that overlap was more,
if the wave function

00:46:57.190 --> 00:46:58.390
going into the middle--

00:47:02.840 --> 00:47:08.270
if this is the nucleus
and this is the electron,

00:47:08.270 --> 00:47:13.340
and the wave function of the
s orbital looks like this,

00:47:13.340 --> 00:47:21.830
and it's almost 0, that's
why we are alive today.

00:47:21.830 --> 00:47:28.090
But if this looks more like
this, no, we wouldn't make it.

00:47:28.090 --> 00:47:30.610
There's just too much
probability for the electron

00:47:30.610 --> 00:47:35.140
to decay into the nucleus, and
give off that amount of energy,

00:47:35.140 --> 00:47:37.150
and the atom collapses.

00:47:39.850 --> 00:47:44.375
So we should be very thankful
to quantum mechanics.

00:47:44.375 --> 00:47:47.660
Now, there are
situations, though,

00:47:47.660 --> 00:47:52.300
when you actually
have nodes in between.

00:47:52.300 --> 00:47:54.340
And that's a tougher one.

00:47:54.340 --> 00:47:56.550
The node means the wave
function goes exactly to 0.

00:47:56.550 --> 00:48:00.240
Now what's happening?

00:48:00.240 --> 00:48:02.820
And here, we go
back to this world

00:48:02.820 --> 00:48:06.480
of particles, this field
theory world, basically, of how

00:48:06.480 --> 00:48:10.260
particles move, by essentially
annihilating themselves

00:48:10.260 --> 00:48:12.590
and reappearing.

00:48:12.590 --> 00:48:15.910
That's how electrons
really move.

00:48:15.910 --> 00:48:19.030
Now any questions
about any of that?

00:48:25.560 --> 00:48:26.970
No questions at all?

00:48:26.970 --> 00:48:31.920
OK, we're going to
start taking this

00:48:31.920 --> 00:48:35.280
to the next level,
which is obviously going

00:48:35.280 --> 00:48:38.713
to have to be more complexity.

00:48:38.713 --> 00:48:40.880
There are some constants
that I'm just putting here.

00:48:40.880 --> 00:48:42.470
I'm not going to
spend any time on it,

00:48:42.470 --> 00:48:44.120
but these are the
constants you'll

00:48:44.120 --> 00:48:46.580
be using in the quantum world.

00:48:46.580 --> 00:48:49.310
We have an electron
volt. We have a Rydberg,

00:48:49.310 --> 00:48:51.620
which is 13.6 electron volts.

00:48:51.620 --> 00:48:53.370
And just to make it
interesting, there's

00:48:53.370 --> 00:48:57.200
a Hartree, which
is a half of that.

00:48:57.200 --> 00:49:01.090
And then the same with
angstroms and Bohr.

00:49:01.090 --> 00:49:02.680
These are the kinds of unit--

00:49:02.680 --> 00:49:05.110
do you say angstrom,
do you say Bohr--

00:49:05.110 --> 00:49:09.190
to-may-to, to-mah-to--
you can choose, but just

00:49:09.190 --> 00:49:11.700
keep track of it all.

00:49:11.700 --> 00:49:13.720
Now, as we go to more complex--

00:49:13.720 --> 00:49:17.670
so I've given you a
particle in a box,

00:49:17.670 --> 00:49:20.490
and then I gave you a
particle, actually, on Tuesday,

00:49:20.490 --> 00:49:22.140
in an oscillator.

00:49:22.140 --> 00:49:25.270
And then I give you a
particle in 1 over r.

00:49:25.270 --> 00:49:26.800
And that got us a long way.

00:49:26.800 --> 00:49:28.060
We explained spectral lines.

00:49:28.060 --> 00:49:30.520
We got hydrogen right.

00:49:30.520 --> 00:49:32.770
But if I just add a little
bit more complexity,

00:49:32.770 --> 00:49:36.060
you see things get really messy.

00:49:36.060 --> 00:49:38.280
Now, this was a problem.

00:49:38.280 --> 00:49:41.550
I wanted to show
how messy things get

00:49:41.550 --> 00:49:47.340
with analytic solutions as a
kind of motivational exercise.

00:49:47.340 --> 00:49:48.870
So I gave this on
a homework problem

00:49:48.870 --> 00:49:51.610
in this class two years ago.

00:49:51.610 --> 00:49:57.600
And I'll admit that
was probably a mistake.

00:49:57.600 --> 00:50:04.260
I had a lot of people at
office hours, because you see,

00:50:04.260 --> 00:50:05.220
this is the same thing.

00:50:05.220 --> 00:50:07.050
I'm throwing my
quantum mechanical ball

00:50:07.050 --> 00:50:09.090
into a wall that has
another wall behind it.

00:50:11.800 --> 00:50:13.840
So can't you just set it up?

00:50:13.840 --> 00:50:15.370
Well, sure, you can.

00:50:15.370 --> 00:50:17.860
And this is what you get.

00:50:17.860 --> 00:50:21.130
And you put that
into Mathematica,

00:50:21.130 --> 00:50:24.370
which every single student
did, and it chokes--

00:50:24.370 --> 00:50:25.960
can't do it.

00:50:25.960 --> 00:50:27.190
Too many for Matlab.

00:50:30.280 --> 00:50:32.440
I guess too many boundary
conditions, or too many

00:50:32.440 --> 00:50:34.540
variables, or
something, but nobody

00:50:34.540 --> 00:50:37.000
could get Mathematica
to do this without

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:39.340
some intelligent substitution
of variables first,

00:50:39.340 --> 00:50:40.660
which was sort of the trick.

00:50:40.660 --> 00:50:44.380
But my point in this was
not to make students suffer.

00:50:44.380 --> 00:50:46.510
I don't like to do
that, but it was just

00:50:46.510 --> 00:50:48.430
to convey how hard
this equation gets

00:50:48.430 --> 00:50:53.050
to solve with just a little
bit more complexity than one

00:50:53.050 --> 00:50:57.400
particle in a well or in 1
over r, or something like that.

00:50:57.400 --> 00:51:03.510
It gets really hard, and
that's why we need computers.

00:51:03.510 --> 00:51:06.690
And that's what computation
in the last 50 years has done.

00:51:06.690 --> 00:51:09.780
It has made this, together
with some algorithms,

00:51:09.780 --> 00:51:13.080
some simplifications
that you'll hear about--

00:51:13.080 --> 00:51:17.250
it has made this
equation solvable

00:51:17.250 --> 00:51:20.970
for much more complex systems.

00:51:20.970 --> 00:51:23.760
So I can also say,
well, let's not

00:51:23.760 --> 00:51:26.050
make the potential
more complicated.

00:51:26.050 --> 00:51:31.800
Let's just add another electron.

00:51:31.800 --> 00:51:35.880
So now, I'm still with
a 1 over r potential,

00:51:35.880 --> 00:51:38.740
but I've got two of them.

00:51:38.740 --> 00:51:41.950
So now, all of a sudden,
my potential term

00:51:41.950 --> 00:51:45.970
is these electrons
interacting with the proton,

00:51:45.970 --> 00:51:50.050
but also those electrons
interacting with each other.

00:51:50.050 --> 00:51:54.600
That's r12, the distance
between the two electrons.

00:51:54.600 --> 00:51:56.760
And boy, does that
make this equation

00:51:56.760 --> 00:52:00.090
hard to solve analytically.

00:52:00.090 --> 00:52:05.650
You cannot use
separation of variables.

00:52:05.650 --> 00:52:12.450
So even just one more electron,
it's a deal breaker, basically.

00:52:12.450 --> 00:52:15.960
And now you think we
want to do big molecules.

00:52:15.960 --> 00:52:17.160
We want to do fullerenes.

00:52:17.160 --> 00:52:19.530
We want to do silicon.

00:52:19.530 --> 00:52:22.450
We want to do
thousands of electrons.

00:52:22.450 --> 00:52:24.270
Analytic approaches won't work.

00:52:26.810 --> 00:52:28.380
So what can you do?

00:52:28.380 --> 00:52:32.990
Well, there are two
different ways to go.

00:52:32.990 --> 00:52:34.760
You've got to do something.

00:52:34.760 --> 00:52:39.470
You've got to make it easier,
because as you'll see,

00:52:39.470 --> 00:52:43.880
an exact solution, even with
the most powerful computers

00:52:43.880 --> 00:52:48.950
in the world times squared
are not going to do it.

00:52:48.950 --> 00:52:52.010
You need to make approximations
to the actual equation.

00:52:52.010 --> 00:52:55.530
And you'll hear about
those next week.

00:52:55.530 --> 00:52:58.980
And one thing you can do is
you can use perturbation theory

00:52:58.980 --> 00:53:03.360
to say that this Hamiltonian
is actually some simpler

00:53:03.360 --> 00:53:05.430
Hamiltonian.

00:53:05.430 --> 00:53:08.190
That Hamiltonian is
some simpler Hamiltonian

00:53:08.190 --> 00:53:12.300
that you can solve easily
plus some perturbation to it.

00:53:12.300 --> 00:53:14.640
We're not going
to really do that.

00:53:14.640 --> 00:53:18.070
Has anybody used
perturbation theory?

00:53:18.070 --> 00:53:20.280
So we're not going
to do it much but,

00:53:20.280 --> 00:53:22.360
I'm just using it for reference.

00:53:22.360 --> 00:53:25.530
And then, so you do
something for something.

00:53:25.530 --> 00:53:28.710
Perturbation theory, what you do
is you say, well, that's hard,

00:53:28.710 --> 00:53:30.130
so I'm not going to do that.

00:53:30.130 --> 00:53:32.490
But this is actually kind
of related, and it's easy,

00:53:32.490 --> 00:53:33.960
and I know how to do this.

00:53:33.960 --> 00:53:37.500
So I'll do this and then
add something to it.

00:53:37.500 --> 00:53:40.710
That's basically
perturbation theory.

00:53:40.710 --> 00:53:43.470
But what we're
going to do is we're

00:53:43.470 --> 00:53:48.630
going to try to solve it using
more of a matrix eigenvalue

00:53:48.630 --> 00:53:49.330
approach.

00:53:49.330 --> 00:53:51.960
And again, we are not going
to go deep into the math here.

00:53:51.960 --> 00:53:55.830
And you will not be
tested on the math.

00:53:55.830 --> 00:53:59.250
As I said, my goal here
is to have you guys

00:53:59.250 --> 00:54:04.410
applying these equations
to real materials problems.

00:54:04.410 --> 00:54:08.160
But I do think that it's useful
to know what's under the hood,

00:54:08.160 --> 00:54:10.440
to know what equations
are being solved

00:54:10.440 --> 00:54:12.900
when you press "Simulate."

00:54:12.900 --> 00:54:16.440
So you'll hear more
about this, and how

00:54:16.440 --> 00:54:19.740
you go about actually
making these approximations,

00:54:19.740 --> 00:54:21.210
making the
approximations you need

00:54:21.210 --> 00:54:27.690
to make in order to get
an eigenvalue problem that

00:54:27.690 --> 00:54:29.870
can be solved on a computer.

00:54:29.870 --> 00:54:31.870
There are a couple of
different ways to do that.

00:54:31.870 --> 00:54:33.995
The way that we're going
to settle on in this class

00:54:33.995 --> 00:54:35.827
is density functional theory.

00:54:35.827 --> 00:54:37.410
So we'll talk a
little bit about that.

00:54:37.410 --> 00:54:40.050
And again, the only Nobel
Prize in computation

00:54:40.050 --> 00:54:42.720
was given for that, the
development of that theory.

00:54:45.640 --> 00:54:48.070
Now, there's one more
thing I need to talk about

00:54:48.070 --> 00:54:52.030
before I move to just
a couple of examples

00:54:52.030 --> 00:54:54.850
online that I'd
like to show you.

00:54:54.850 --> 00:54:58.340
And that is that there's
something still missing here.

00:54:58.340 --> 00:55:12.690
So we've got-- let's
see, we've got this 1s.

00:55:12.690 --> 00:55:15.270
So now we know where
these things come from.

00:55:15.270 --> 00:55:17.370
We really know where they
come from, the solution

00:55:17.370 --> 00:55:18.720
to the hydrogen atom--

00:55:21.250 --> 00:55:27.890
2p, 3s, and so on.

