00:57:32.100 --> 00:57:35.220
But classically, you see, if
you have charged spinning,

00:57:35.220 --> 00:57:36.780
you get a magnetic field.

00:57:36.780 --> 00:57:41.040
Classically, if you shoot this
through a really large magnet,

00:57:41.040 --> 00:57:44.250
you should just get a whole
range of lines of fields.

00:57:44.250 --> 00:57:48.450
But just like the double slit,
it didn't turn out that way.

00:57:48.450 --> 00:57:53.360
You got two dots
instead, only two dots.

00:57:53.360 --> 00:57:54.460
And these are very famous.

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:56.290
These are the
Stern-Gerlach experiments,

00:57:56.290 --> 00:57:58.810
which were done all
around the same time they

00:57:58.810 --> 00:58:00.190
were figuring all this out.

00:58:00.190 --> 00:58:04.000
And what it showed is that the
spin can only be up or down.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:06.850
It can only be two things.

00:58:06.850 --> 00:58:12.040
There's only two values for the
spin of an electron, the spin

00:58:12.040 --> 00:58:14.200
being the thing that's
causing this thing

00:58:14.200 --> 00:58:17.830
to have a magnetic moment
that's causing it to react

00:58:17.830 --> 00:58:20.825
to the external magnetic field.

00:58:20.825 --> 00:58:23.260
You should get a line.

00:58:23.260 --> 00:58:25.090
You should get all this--

00:58:25.090 --> 00:58:28.900
classically, electrons should
have any spin they want.

00:58:28.900 --> 00:58:31.510
I don't know what that
was, but it should be

00:58:31.510 --> 00:58:33.400
able to point in any direction.

00:58:33.400 --> 00:58:36.040
But no, it can only point
this way or this way.

00:58:36.040 --> 00:58:39.170
