01:00:34.800 --> 01:00:35.597
Yes.

01:00:35.597 --> 01:00:37.680
AUDIENCE: Two fermions
can't be in the same state.

01:00:37.680 --> 01:00:41.400
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: OK, so two
electrons, we'll just say,

01:00:41.400 --> 01:00:44.470
which are fermions, cannot
be in the same state.

01:00:44.470 --> 01:00:47.370
And what do you mean
by the "same state?"

01:00:47.370 --> 01:00:53.970
AUDIENCE: That they can be in
sort of the same energy shell

01:00:53.970 --> 01:00:56.880
with the same spin
at the same time.

01:00:56.880 --> 01:00:58.290
JEFFREY GROSSMAN: OK, very good.

01:00:58.290 --> 01:01:00.840
Basically what it means is
they cannot have the exact same

01:01:00.840 --> 01:01:01.530
quantum numbers.

01:01:04.530 --> 01:01:09.290
Pauli exclusion says
you cannot do this.

01:01:09.290 --> 01:01:12.290
Now, I mentioned you
can violate Hund's rule.

01:01:12.290 --> 01:01:15.410
And you can violate
Hund's rule by having

01:01:15.410 --> 01:01:18.230
degenerate orbitals
with the same energy,

01:01:18.230 --> 01:01:20.570
and doing it there.

01:01:20.570 --> 01:01:21.920
But usually, you don't.

01:01:21.920 --> 01:01:25.640
Pauli exclusion is an
incredibly important aspect

01:01:25.640 --> 01:01:26.720
of quantum mechanics.

01:01:26.720 --> 01:01:30.500
It says that no two
electrons, fermions,

01:01:30.500 --> 01:01:32.720
can occupy the same
set of quantum numbers

01:01:32.720 --> 01:01:33.830
when you include spin.

01:01:36.480 --> 01:01:40.560
That is what gives us literally
the periodic table and all

01:01:40.560 --> 01:01:43.920
of chemistry when you add
that to quantum mechanics.

01:01:43.920 --> 01:01:49.370
That is what gives us the rest,
that plus the hydrogen atom.

01:01:49.370 --> 01:01:51.560
You don't need much
more, except you do.

01:01:51.560 --> 01:01:58.880
